<br>
The DKP is clearly the capitalistic idealogy applied to EQ where the monatary unit is time.  People that are time rich irl will get more DKPs, people thare not will have a lot less DKPs.  When there is a semi uniform distribution of time available, for all guild members, the capitalistic way works wonders.<br>
<br>
When your guild consists of two classes of people: the people that basically play all the time and those that can not play all the time (due to what ever circumstances beyond their control), the DKPs are going to bias all of the loot towards the people that play the most and that seems to imply that the over all guild strength will be lesser than it could conceivably be, by a lot.<br>
<br>
<br>
Example:  Resist Kits.  A needed part of the equipment that a raiding character needs.  If only a subset of your guild has these then, you are not as strong as if everyone had them  (ie on the first AE some large subset of your raiding party eats its or loses massive HPs).<br>
<br>
Apply this to: damage output by the guild per time period.  The DKP system will not maximize this attribute as we have two different classes of players where one class can never afford the really great items.  The assumption is that due to the fact there is always something better and that I do not play that often I should ALWAYS hoard my DKPs so I can, at some point in the future, have enough to make my one giant purchase and get that uber item.  Yet, the entire time that guild member is attending raids with their sub optimal weapons and gear (as they are saving up for the big uber item) they are actually harming the guild. (as they are not optimally equiped at this time period as they could be due to items rotting).<br>
<br>
<br>
This seems especially evident where no drop rotting items occurs.  I can get a +3 ac increase for the cost of 2 DKPs which is a irl cost of N hours and I look and say: &quot;NO WAY I am saving up for the uber item!&quot;<br>
<br>
For the next D days (D is until I get the uber item I am savng up for that increased my ac by 5)  I am 3 ac less than I could have been.  If we are trying to maximize the guild's over all effectiveness it seems this is a bad thing.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Also the DKP system seems to implicitly force people away from thinking:  &quot;for the good of the guild&quot;  (as evidenced by lack of members attending non DKP raids) and more towards:  &quot;I must maximize the number of DKPs I have and that is all I care about.&quot;  ie.  why should I help others get a sleepers key when there exists enough people to do the sleepers tomb right now?  More competition for the loot I want is a BAD BAD thing.  Keep them out!<br>
<br>
I guess if you have an alan greenspan type person (ie guild gm / officers) thinking: &quot;I want the guild to be strong and to do that I need more people with sleepers keys, so I will modify the system to add IDKPs so that I have control over giving these out.  And now I will up the probability of a lotto such that the IDKPs are worth a bunch.  BOOM more people into sleepers.&quot;<br>
<br>
That works but it seems that it might be better to have that impetus come from within the guild?  (not certain on this)<br>
