<br>
IDKP is used as a modifier to your base DKP.  When you buy an item it technically just gets subtracted from your DKP total and then the new number is then modified by your IDKP.  You might see it as losing IDKP because your DKP+IDKP total goes down but you never actually pay for an item with IDKP.  So for example, if you have 6 &quot;total&quot; IDKP+DKP but that number is derived from -2 DKP and 8 IDKP, then you could not buy an item because you cannot afford it (unless it was no drop).<br>
<br>
I didn't really want to get into the periodic IDKP negative adjustment... but here it goes:  <br>
<br>
We have an &quot;active&quot; list of players and &quot;non-active&quot; list of players.  Those &quot;active&quot; players all receive a periodic adjustment in IDKP each week or so.  The amount subtracted is exactly the same for every &quot;active&quot; player and the amount is based on how many total IDKP could have been earned since the last adjustment.  When we 1st introduced this system there were MANY complaints coming from within the guild until people understood how it works.  The primary concern was &quot;you mean I lose DKP each week?!&quot;.  The answer is no, you only lose IDKP each week which affects your standing in lottos.  So lets say in a given week if you attended every possible raid you got 3.0 IDKP.  Lets say another player attended no raids.. thus gaining 0.0 IDKP.  At the end of the week, an across-the-board adjustment is made (I believe this adjustment is calculated as &quot;the sum of all IDKP given out to players in a period divided by the total number of active players&quot;.  Lets say this number came out to be 1.6 for the example above.  All players then lose 1.6 IDKP from their total.  Now here's the part ppl normally don't understand... you are NOT losing DKP... you are simply losing points that get allocated to you lotto modifer.  And because ALL members are losing the same amount, it doesn't matter what that number is.  The end result is that the 1st player gained +1.4 modifer to DKP lottos, and the end player loses 1.6.  This system was implemented to further ensure that the ppl who attend the most raids get the best chance of looting what they want the soonest.  In addition, yes it CAN penalize you for not showing up to raids... but objectively this will only happen if you attend less than half the raids in a given week.  Those that attend all the raids are rewarded the most... those that attend ~ half neither gain nor lose... and those that attend very few raids per week are penalized at lottos.<br>
<br>
You can be taken off the &quot;active&quot; list if you know you are going to be taking a leave of absence from the game for a while.  This will ensure that when you come back you won't be rolling in lottos at -154.2 DKP because of all the raids you missed.  However, if and when you do come back, you cannot use your old DKP immediately... it wouldn't be fair to have someone come back after we (for example) had started killing all 4 warders routinely and have them scoff up 4 loots in a row because they used to have a lot of DKP in the past.  So there's a &quot;freeze&quot; on your lotto privledges when you come back to ensure this doesn't happen... after a month or two and you've proven you have come back &quot;to stay&quot; then you can use your DKP again.<br>
<br>
There's one thing to keep in mind when thinking about this IDKP system (ESPECIALLY if you might use it).  Afterlife is a raid guild...we raid usually 6 nights a week and we need as many people to show up to these raids as possible.  24 players just doesn't cut it anymore for raids... we need more... and in order to get more we needed to provide incentive to come... or penalties for not coming.  Most of the players in AL are pretty hardcore...90% of the &quot;active&quot; list does not lose any IDKP each week when the adjustment is put out.  People who do start to lose a lot of IDKP each week might reconsider if AL is the best guild for them.  We need players who can show up almost every night... and our system is designed to reward those that do... while possibly penalizing the casual players.  Everyone in AL is comfortable with this &quot;agreement&quot; that was made among members.  In other guilds... there may be a higher number of casual players which would resent this portion of our system.  <br>
<br>
