<br>
First a little joke system... This system is called Ebay Loot Whore or ELW for short.  The system goes like this, every non-no drop item is put onto ebay and sold to the highest bidder.  The money for that item is split evenly inbetween those guild members who were there when the item dropped.  If someone in the guild wants the item, they can pay real $ for it.  No drop items would be auctioned off for real $ in guildchat between those members who are there for the raid.  I find the concept hilarious <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  and even fair although the fact that people from outside the guild can buy the item if they want isnt entirely fair but hey this isnt a serious system anyhow <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
Anyhow back to real systems and DKP. <br>
Example 1: Gnome mask drops and Thott has the most points (168 points) so he gets for 1 point. UberNoob01 has 30 points and wants to spend all 30 on the mask but can't. This is seen as fair since Thott had the most points.  <br>
<br>
Now switch around the variables a bit.  <br>
Example2: A ride to the space station alpha costs $1 million dollars.  Bill Gates has the most money of anyone ($100 billion) so he gets the ride for $1 million.  Not so rich investment banker Dennis Tito had $100 million and wanted to spend $20 million dollars for the ride to the space station but can't. This is seen as fair since Bill Gates has the most dollars.  <br>
<br>
What is wrong with this picture?  The primary problem in DKP is that net worth is the basis for determining who gets items combined with prices not being set by the market (causing artificially low prices to prevent rotting caused when the price is too high).  In example 1 thott is getting an item worth 30 points at fair market price for only 1 point.  This situation also leads to thott being first in line for the next item that drops as well which he will also get at less than market value.  Since every point took the same ammount of effort to obtain in the system, UberNoob01 put in the same ammount of effort to get his 30 points that thott put in to get 30 of his points so there is no fair justification for saying thott should get the item ahead of ubernoob01.  What DKP is saying implicitly is that Thotts points are worth more than everyone elses for the simple reason that he has more of them then anyone else.  Furthermore each individual contribution he makes to the guild is worth more than anyone else.  Thott going from 138 to 168 points was worth more to the guild than UberNoob01 going from 0 to 30 points.<br>
<br>
What an auction system does is determine what the market price of an item is.  In the long run, thott will get his 168 points worth of gear and UberNoob01 will get his 30 points. If Thott wants his gnome mask more than ubernoob01 then he should have to pay more than ubernoob01 or just wait till the next mask drops if he doesnt think it is worth 30 points.  It also acts as a great drain on the entire economy as there is no longer such a huge incentive to hoard points.  Hoarding becomes useful for getting the latest and greatest item when it drops if you really want to pay the markup for a brand new item. If ubernoob01s greatest EQ goal is to look like a gnome bard (damn that would rock <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) then he should have the option of wasting his points to get the first gnome mask that drops.  If Dennis Tito wants to spend his dollars to be the first space tourist then go right ahead. Eventually the supply will grow to meet the demand and the price will drop to whatever it should be (price of additional item = cost of obtaining 1 additional item). However that first few trip into space is going to be very expensive since there is a huge demand and a supply of only 1 (as opposed to a supply of 2 when the next ride occurs).<br>
<br>
Note: These are all theoretical arguements. Thott runs the guild and can do whatever the hell he pleases much like Zaar runs mine and can do whatever the hell he pleases. A system is fair when its users believe it to be fair.  However when compared to a pure capitalist economy I believe DKP to have flaws as described above.<br>
